## Features Classification MLLIB

%pyspark
from pyspark.ml.regression import RandomForestRegressor
from pyspark.ml.regression import LinearRegression

%pyspark
from pyspark.ml.feature import VectorAssembler

data = meters_db.join(information_households.select(["METER_ID","CAT"]),meters_db.METER_ID==information_households.METER_ID).drop(information_households.METER_ID)
#data.show(5)

#Dataframe to pandas array
data2=data.toPandas()
#print(len(data2))
cat1=data2.loc[data2['CAT'] == 1]
cat2=data2.loc[data2['CAT'] == 2]
cat3=data2.loc[data2['CAT'] == 3]


#Resize to cat with least records
records=np.min([len(cat1),len(cat2),len(cat3)])
#Resize to cat with least records
cat1=cat1[0:records]
cat2=cat2[0:records]
cat3=cat3[0:records]

data2=cat1.append(cat2).append(cat3)
#print("Data resized to "+str(len(data2)/3)+" records per category.\nTotal records: "+str(len(data2)))
feature_names = ['MEAN_MONTH', 'MEAN_HD', 'MEAN_WD', 'MEAN_SD', 'MEAN_MAX', 'MEAN_MAX_H', 'MEAN_MAX_H_TIME']
X = data2[feature_names]
y = data2['CAT']

data3 = spark.createDataFrame(data2)    
vectorAssembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols = ['MEAN_MONTH', 'MEAN_HD', 'MEAN_WD', 'MEAN_SD', 'MEAN_MAX', 'MEAN_MAX_H', 'MEAN_MAX_H_TIME'], outputCol = 'features')
X_df = vectorAssembler.transform(data3)
X_df = X_df.select(['features', 'CAT'])

%pyspark
from pyspark.ml.feature import MinMaxScaler
from pyspark.mllib.evaluation import MulticlassMetrics
from pyspark.ml.classification import LogisticRegression
from pyspark.ml.evaluation import MulticlassClassificationEvaluator

# Compute summary statistics and generate MinMaxScalerModel
scaler = MinMaxScaler(inputCol="features", outputCol="scaledFeatures")
scalerModel = scaler.fit(X_df)

# rescale each feature to range [min, max].
scaledData = scalerModel.transform(X_df)
print("Features scaled to range: [%f, %f]" % (scaler.getMin(), scaler.getMax()))

#Choose between featues or scaled features
#feature_select="features"
feature_select="scaledFeatures"

data_ready=scaledData.select(feature_select,"CAT")

#Specify train and test percentage
train_porc=0.7
test_porc=1-train_porc
splits = data_ready.randomSplit([train_porc,test_porc])
train_df = splits[0]
test_df = splits[1]
#print(data_ready.count())
#print(train_df.count())
#print(test_df.count())



# Load training data
lr = LogisticRegression(featuresCol = feature_select, labelCol='CAT',maxIter=1000)

# Fit the model
lrModel = lr.fit(train_df)

# compute accuracy on the train set
result = lrModel.transform(train_df)
predictionAndLabels = result.select("prediction", "CAT")
evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="CAT", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="accuracy")
print("Train set accuracy = " + str(evaluator.evaluate(predictionAndLabels)))

# compute accuracy on the test set
result = lrModel.transform(test_df)
predictionAndLabels = result.select("prediction", "CAT")
evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="CAT", predictionCol="prediction",metricName="accuracy")
print("Test set accuracy = " + str(evaluator.evaluate(predictionAndLabels)))

predictionAndLabels=(predictionAndLabels
        .withColumn('CAT',(col('CAT')).cast(DoubleType())))

#To spark df so we can apply Metrics
predictionAndLabels_df = sc.parallelize(predictionAndLabels.collect())
metrics = MulticlassMetrics(predictionAndLabels_df)

precision = metrics.precision()
recall = metrics.recall()
f1Score = metrics.fMeasure()
print("Summary Stats")
print("Precision = %s" % precision)
print("Recall = %s" % recall)
print("F1 Score = %s" % f1Score)
print(metrics.confusionMatrix())
